title: For Sale:  Browning Lever Action Rifle (BLR) Model 81 with Leupold Scope M8
postcontent:
With a timeless beauty that’s more than skin deep, the BLR Lightweight ’81 is ready and waiting to be your next lever-action hunting rifle. The gloss finish on the Walnut straight grip stock contrasts beautifully with the deeply polished blue finish on the receiver and the barrel. This is what a serious lever-action rifle should be, and what every other lever-action wishes it was.

-The button-Rifled barrel is triple-checked for straightness and interior finish and then air-gauged to ensure a consistent diameter throughout the bore’s length.
-Individually finished with a hand-reamed chamber for tighter tolerances and more precise headspace.
-The barrel’s target-type Crown enables a more uniform release of gas as the bullet exits the muzzle, helping prevent any unwanted shift in bullet trajectory. The barrel Crown is recessed to help protect it from accidental impact damage that can degrade accuracy.
-Low-Profile adjustable square notch rear sight and a high-visibility front blade with gold bead fitted on a raised ramp-style base.?
-Richly blued steel finish on all external surfaces --  a stunning reflection of the gunmaker’s art.
-Aircraft grade alloy receiver is precision machined to provide outstanding reliability and years of dependable service.
-The slick-sided receiver houses the BLR’s lightning fast, glass-smooth rack and pinion lever action.
-Rrotating multi-lug bolt head that locks into the barrel extension to produce bolt-action accuracy and magnum-level strength.
-The BLR is one of the few lever-action rifle designs that is strong enough to use today’s most popular magnum cartridges, giving you the extended reach and flat bullet trajectory other lever-action owners can only dream of.
-Recessed bolt face that surrounds the cartridge head for added strength and lasting dependability.
-The BLR’s generously-sized side ejection port allows fired cases to instantly clear the action without hitting you or your scope and bouncing back onto the receiver, potentially creating a jam.
-The folding hammer on the BLR provides an added measure of safety when the hammer is at half-cock, having two positions in that mode so the status of the rifle can be instantly seen and felt.
-The folding hammer on the BLR has four basic positions; Full-cock, half-cock, folded hammer position and the dropped or fired position.
-The trigger is unique in that it travels along with the lever as it’s cycled, meaning that pinching your fingers between the lever and trigger on closing the action is a thing of the past.
-Fingerpiece on the BLR’s trigger is nice and wide with vertical friction ribs to prevent your finger from slipping, giving you more precise trigger control for those demanding long-range shots.
-The detachable steel box magazine makes for quick reloading, both in the field and on the range.
-Unlike lever actions with tubular magazines, the BLR’s detachable steel box magazine lets you use aerodynamically-superior pointed bullets, which opens up a whole new world of ballistic performance that is usually found in bolt-action and autoloading rifles.
-Magazine capacity is 3 rounds in the magnum calibers and 4 rounds in standard calibers.
-Stock sculpted from fine Walnut and the cut checkering in the grip and fore-end is crisply executed for lasting good looks and a more solid grip.
-The straight grip BLR stock is true to the classic lines of the lever action rifle and has a traditional carbine strap at the fore-end.
-Stock has a deep, glossy finish that brings out every nuance of the wood’s warm color and grain.
-The well-formed recoil pad helps reduce felt recoil and flinching.
-Steel sling swivel studs are pre-installed for easy mounting of your sling or bipod.

 The Sigma was Smith & Wesson 's first venture into using synthetic materials in gun construction, using high-strength polymer material for the frame. The gun is similar to a Glock safe-action pistol in both its design and operation, leading to some controversy and speculation as to the legality of the gun's patents.

 In 1999 Smith & Wesson introduced the VE series. These models were billed as 'enhanced' and featured an improved grip, improved trigger, and enlarged ejection port. This model returned to the black coloration of the polymer frame mated with a stainless steel or black melonite slide.

 At this time Smith & Wesson retired the 4.5 inch barrel and switched all Sigmas to the 4.0 inch barrel. Sigmas from this era onward are considered '2nd generation' Sigmas. Shortly after the introduction of the VE series, Smith & Wesson further improved it by adding an accessory rail but did not change the model number to reflect this update.

title: For Sale:  Meigs .50 calber Lever Slide Repeater
postcontent:
Meigs .50 Caliber Lever Slide Repeater 
Invented in 1866 by Captain J. Vincent Meigs, the Meigs .50 cal was an early expirement with repeating rifles. The most notable feature of the rifle was the 50 round removable magazine that was contained in a tube located in the buttstock. It was a lever action firearm, and could practically fire 50 rounds a minute, something not seen again until the introduction of semi auto rifles.
Only three of these prototypes would be made, one was fired 38,000 times without malfunction. Unfortunatly this gun was too expensive and too difficult to manufacture at the time. The Meigs rifle would never go into production.
One can be found on display at the Cody Firearms Museum, Cody, Wyoming.

postcontent: Seller Stock #: HGE26R9BU Photo is a representative from a handful of very similar pistols. This listing is for One pistol. Here is one of a few All German Sig-Sauer P-226, 9mm Pistols that served our country with the US Department of Energy, special response team duty, protecting our Nuclear Plants. According to their JJ date codes, they were manufactured in 1988. Manufacturer was Sig Sauer gmbh of Eckernförde, Germany. Importer was Sig Arms of Herndon, Virginia, and the slide is so marked. Type is locked breech hammer fired traditional single and double action semi automatic pistol. Construction is steel slide, barrel, trigger, hammer, and internal parts all assembled into a lightweight alloy grip frame. Barrel, frame, and slide all bear matching serial numbers. Chambering is 9mm Luger, 9mm Parabellum, 9x19, call it what you will, THE 9mm. Barrel is 4 1/4 inch with six groove 1: 9.75 right hand rifling. Slide has serrated rear lateral surfaces and is 1.02 wide at the port. Slide has a removable breech block. Sights are steel dovetailed, white dot front and white bar rear, drift adjustable only for windage. Trigger is .350 serrated face combat type, housed inside a square trigger guard. Hammer is .312 serrated spur. Trigger is two stage on double action, 1/4 inch to engagement with 1 inch of travel to fire position, 12 pound vicinity pull. Single action pull is two stage as well, about 1/4 inch to engagement with a crisp original 4 pound pull. Sigs all have a firing pin block safety that prevents accidental discharge if the pistol is dropped, yet even with that, they always have the best single action trigger pull of all from the factory. Grips are factory black polymer. Each 226 comes with One original factory issue Sig Sauer 15 shot magazine, so fully loaded capacity of 16 rounds. Weight empty is 31 ounces, with center of gravity just forward of the magazine release. Weight fully loaded is approximately 42 ounces. Surface detractions on this specimen and its mates are minimal to moderate. Each one of them underwent an armory refinish at some point, and shows faint residual edge wear to the frame and strut, with dimness to the slide lettering. Grips show some wear on the right panel as the photos show.
